## Research Notes

**Textbook approach**: 
Ukrainian primer textbooks (bukvars) like Bolshakova (2018) and Zaharijchuk (NUS 2025) do not teach the alphabet in A-B-C order. Instead, they group letters by phonetic simplicity and word-building utility. They introduce highly productive vowels (А, О, У) alongside basic, continuous consonants (М, Л, Н, С). This allows learners to immediately form and read open syllables (МА, ЛА), closed syllables (АМ, ОН), and their first decodable words (мама, сом, ананас) without needing to know the rest of the alphabet.

**Common errors for English speakers**:
1. **Visual False Friends**: English speakers frequently misread the Cyrillic Н as the English /h/ and the Cyrillic С as the English /k/ (like in "cat"). 
2. **Vowel Reduction**: English speakers instinctively reduce unstressed vowels to a schwa /ə/ sound. The most critical error is reducing an unstressed Ukrainian О to an /a/ or /ə/ sound (which happens in Russian, but never in Ukrainian).

**Cultural hook**: 
The Cyrillic script was not actually created by Saints Cyril and Methodius themselves (they created the Glagolitic script). Cyrillic was developed later by their students in the First Bulgarian Empire, who adapted Greek letters and added new symbols to represent unique Slavic sounds.

**Cross-references**: 
This module builds the absolute foundation of literacy and connects directly to `a1-02` (The Cyrillic Code II), which will introduce 7 new letters and rely entirely on the syllable blending mechanics taught in this lesson.